r 1431","1364–1431":"1364–1431","1377–1432":"1377–1432","1396–1453":"1396–1453","1402–1455":"1402–1455","–1453":"–1453","1653–1657":"1653–1657","1657–Male":"1657–Deceased","–1400":"–1400","1375–1395":"1375–1395","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","abt 1364":"about 1364","1657":"1657","1402":"1402","22 December 1431":"22 December 1431","1400":"1400","1653":"1653","1455":"1455","1432":"1432","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1431":"1431","1375":"1375","1364":"1364","about 1400":"about 1400","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Durham, England":"Durham, England","Swine, Yorkshire, England":"Swine, Yorkshire, England","Melton Hall, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hilton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire):","habitational name from any of various places called Hilton (e.g. in Cambridgeshire, Derbyshire, Staffordshire, North Yorkshire, and Westmorland), most of which derive from Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some come from Old English <i>helde</i> ‘slope’ + <i>tūn</i>.","occasionally, as in the case of Ralph <i>filius Hilton</i> (Yorkshire 1219), perhaps from the personal name <i>Hilton</i>, itself a possible form of Norman <i>Hildun</i>, composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’ + <i>hūn</i> ‘bear cub’. Compare   Hilt  . This English surname is present in Ireland (mainly taken to Ulster in the early 17th century, though recorded earlier in Dublin)."],"variants":[{"name":"Hylton","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Hilton  ."]},{"name":"Hulton","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Hulton (Lancashire) or Hulton (Staffordshire), both from Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Hilton  ."]},{"name":"Hilt","meanings":["German: from a short form of   Hildebrand   or some other compound ancient Germanic name formed with <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’ as the first element. See   Hild  .","English (London): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hilte</i>, ultimately from ancient Germanic <i>Helto</i>, probably from <i>halith-</i> ‘hero’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":18,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert Hilton Knt. Baron of Hilton was born about 1364, in Yorkshire, England as the son of Sir Robert Hilton and Isabel Hilton. He had at least 3 daughters with Joan Constable. He died on 22 December 1431, in Durham, England, at the age of 68."},"et":{"abt 1364–